{{Politics of Benin}}
A '''constitutional referendum''' was held in the [[Republic of Dahomey]] on 31 March 1968. As with the [[Dahomeyan constitutional referendum, 1964|1964 referendum]], the main issues were changing the system of government to a [[presidential system]], scrapping term limits for the president, and having a [[Unicameralism|unicameral parliament]]. The referendum passed with 92.2% of voters approving the changes. Turnout was 81.8% of the 1,126,155 registered voters.<ref>Nohlen, D, Krennerich, M & Thibaut, B (1999) ''Elections in Africa: A data handbook'', p89 {{ISBN|0-19-829645-2}}</ref>
