{{Politics of Denmark}}
A '''constitutional referendum''' was held in [[Denmark]] on 6 September 1920.<ref name=DN>[[Dieter Nohlen]] & Philip Stöver (2010) ''Elections in Europe: A data handbook'', p524 {{ISBN|978-3-8329-5609-7}}</ref> It was held in order to make changes to the [[Constitution of Denmark|constitution]] of [[Denmark]] from 1915 that had been made necessary to facilitate the reunification of [[South Jutland County|Southern Jutland]] into the kingdom of Denmark.<ref name=NS>Nohlen & Stöver, p532</ref> The changes were approved by 96.9% of voters, with a 49.6% turnout.<ref name=NS/> A total of 614,227 of the 1,291,745 registered voters voted in favour,<ref name=NS/> meaning that 47.6% of eligible voters had voted for the proposals, above the 45% required by the constitution.
