'''''Temple Law Review''''' is a student-edited [[law review]], sponsored by the [[Temple University Beasley School of Law]]. The journal is "dedicated to providing a forum for the expression of new legal thought and scholarly commentary on important developments, trends, and issues in the law."<ref>http://sites.temple.edu/lawreview</ref> Publishing continuously since 1927, Temple Law Review is one of three student journals at [[Temple University Beasley School of Law]].<ref>http://www.law.temple.edu/pages/resources/Publications_Law_Reviews.aspx</ref> Four issues are printed each year, with the Summer issue traditionally focusing on scholarly materials presented during that year's Symposium.<ref>http://sites.temple.edu/lawreview/archive/</ref> Temple Law Review also publishes ''Temple Law Review Online'', a supplement for "scholarly works that are shorter than the traditional law review article, involve time-sensitive topics, or directly respond to materials published in Temple Law Review's printed issues."<ref>https://submissions.scholasticahq.com/temple-law-review-online/about</ref>

== History ==
The journal was founded in 1927 as the ''Temple Law Quarterly''.<ref name="Reilly">{{cite journal |last=Reilly |first=Lawrence J. |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=2002 |month= |title=From Temple Law Quarterly to Temple Law Review - A Historical Survey |journal=Temp. L. Rev. |volume=75 |issue= |page=23 |id= |url=http://sites.temple.edu/lawreview/files/2011/07/Reilly_2002.pdf }}</ref> In its earliest years, the journal covered a wide variety of legal topics, including constitutional law, international law, and legal ethics, with articles and case notes contributed by both students and practicing lawyers.<ref name="Reilly" /> ''Temple Law Quarterly'' scrutinized many twentieth-century developments, publishing articles on patent law's approach to chemical compounds, the consequences of the two World Wars on civil rights and insurance liabilities, the rise of medical malpractice law, and racial discrimination in Pennsylvania Bar admissions.<ref name="Reilly" /> The journal published sixty volumes under the name ''Temple Law Quarterly'', before being renamed the ''Temple Law Review'' in 1988.<ref name="Reilly" />

